<DocsLayout title="Installation" description="Install lean-ctx and configure it for Cursor, GitHub Copilot, Claude Code, and Windsurf.">
  <p>
    lean-ctx is a single Rust binary with zero runtime dependencies. It works as both a transparent
    shell hook and an MCP server for any compatible editor.
  </p>

  <h2>Install</h2>
  <p>Via cargo:</p>
  <pre><code>cargo install lean-ctx</code></pre>

  <p>Or download a prebuilt binary from <a href="https://gitlab.pounce.ch/root/lean-ctx/-/releases">GitLab Releases</a>.</p>

  <p>Or build from source:</p>
  <pre><code>git clone https://gitlab.pounce.ch/root/lean-ctx
cd lean-ctx/rust
cargo build --release
# Binary at: target/release/lean-ctx</code></pre>

  <h2>MCP Server Setup</h2>

  <h3>Cursor</h3>
  <p>Add to <code>~/.cursor/mcp.json</code>:</p>
  <pre><code>{`{
  "mcpServers": {
    "lean-ctx": {
      "command": "lean-ctx"
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>

  <h3>GitHub Copilot</h3>
  <p>Add <code>.github/copilot/mcp.json</code> to your project:</p>
  <pre><code>{`{
  "servers": {
    "lean-ctx": {
      "command": "lean-ctx"
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>

  <h3>Claude Code</h3>
  <pre><code>claude mcp add lean-ctx lean-ctx</code></pre>

  <h3>Windsurf</h3>
  <p>Add to <code>~/.codeium/windsurf/mcp_config.json</code>:</p>
  <pre><code>{`{
  "mcpServers": {
    "lean-ctx": {
      "command": "lean-ctx"
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>

  <h2>Shell Hook Setup</h2>
  <p>
    The shell hook compresses CLI output transparently, without requiring the LLM to use MCP tools.
    Both approaches can be used simultaneously.
  </p>

  <h3>Automatic Setup (Recommended)</h3>
  <p>The fastest way to set up the shell hook — one command installs all aliases globally:</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx init --global</code></pre>
  <p>
    This adds aliases for <code>git</code>, <code>npm</code>, <code>cargo</code>, <code>docker</code>,
    <code>grep</code>, <code>find</code>, <code>ls</code>, and <code>curl</code> to your shell profile
    (<code>.zshrc</code> or <code>.bashrc</code>). Restart your shell or run <code>source ~/.zshrc</code> afterwards.
  </p>

  <h3>Manual Shell Aliases</h3>
  <p>Alternatively, add individual aliases to your <code>.zshrc</code> or <code>.bashrc</code>:</p>
  <pre><code>alias git='lean-ctx -c git'
alias npm='lean-ctx -c npm'
alias cargo='lean-ctx -c cargo'
alias docker='lean-ctx -c docker'
alias grep='lean-ctx -c grep'
alias find='lean-ctx -c find'
alias ls='lean-ctx -c ls'
alias curl='lean-ctx -c curl'</code></pre>

  <h3>Cursor Terminal Profile</h3>
  <p>Add a lean-ctx terminal profile in VS Code / Cursor settings:</p>
  <pre><code>{`{
  "terminal.integrated.profiles.osx": {
    "lean-ctx": {
      "path": "/path/to/lean-ctx",
      "args": ["--shell"],
      "icon": "terminal"
    }
  }
}`}</code></pre>

  <h3>Interactive Shell</h3>
  <p>Run lean-ctx as a shell wrapper:</p>
  <pre><code>lean-ctx --shell</code></pre>

  <h2>Cursor Rule (Optional)</h2>
  <p>
    For maximum token savings, add a Cursor rule to your project. Copy the example from
    <code>examples/lean-ctx.mdc</code> to <code>.cursor/rules/lean-ctx.mdc</code> in your project.
    This instructs the LLM to prefer lean-ctx tools and use compact output.
  </p>

  <h2>Verify Installation</h2>
  <p>After configuring your editor:</p>
  <ol>
    <li>Restart the editor completely</li>
    <li>Open a project file</li>
    <li>Check that 8 tools appear: <code>ctx_read</code>, <code>ctx_tree</code>, <code>ctx_shell</code>,
        <code>ctx_search</code>, <code>ctx_compress</code>, <code>ctx_benchmark</code>,
        <code>ctx_metrics</code>, <code>ctx_analyze</code></li>
    <li>Run <code>ctx_benchmark</code> on a file to verify token counting works</li>
  </ol>
</DocsLayout>
